title: London
description:
London is the capital and largest city of England and the United Kingdom. The ancient City of London (called Londinium, by the Romans), to which the name originally belonged, still retains its mediaeval boundaries, but the name 'London' has long been applied more generally to the whole metropolis which has grown up around it. Londinium built on the north bank of the River Thames in around 50 AD. By the 18th century London was the biggest city in the world. It was the most populous city in the world from 1825 until 1925. 
An important settlement for around two millennia, London is today one of the world's leading business, financial and cultural centres, and its influence in politics, education, entertainment, media, fashion and the arts all contribute to its status as one of the major global cities. It is the largest city in the EU with a population of over 7 million. It will also host the Olympics in 2012.

title: Southwark Council
description:
Southwark council has a population of 274,400 and includes Southwark, Camberwell, Peckham, Bermondsey, Rotherhithe and Dulwich. The north side of the council area has many waterfront developments such as the City Hall and Tate Modern, as well as the rebuilt Globe Theatre and Southwark Cathedral. The main part of the council area is residential including large and diverse communities at Camberwell and Peckham, while Dulwich Village to the south is a preserved village surrounded by residential areas.

http://www.southwark.gov.uk/

title: City of Westminster
description:
The City of Westminster is a London Borough located in Central-West London and is considered a seperate city from the original City of London to the east. 

It is generally considered the centre of modern-day London, and contains within its boundaries the seats of British power and the majority of London's famous sights, including the Houses of Parliament, Buckingham Palace, The West End, Oxford Street and Hyde Park. 

The Houses of Parliament are the headquarters of the British Government. The City of Westminster covers a larger area than Westminster itself, stretching from Kilburn in the North to the Thames in the South, from Hyde Park in the West to Charing Cross in the East.

http://www.westminster.gov.uk/

title: Battersea
description:
Battersea is a district in the London Borough of Wandsworth. For a long time the area was rural, but the Industrial Revolution saw complete development of the area into a very industrial area of London home to many factory labourers. This may have been why when Clapham Junction railway station was built in the area, it was named after Clapham instead - seen then as a wealthier neighbour. The industry slowly declined around the 1970s.  Property development and luxury riverside apartments have changed its character considerably.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2zc7QwtQXtU

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wsz958s1V9c

title: Peckham
description:
Peckham is a large suburban centre in the London Borough of Southwark. It has never had its own Parish or Borough to control but has a strong sense of identity (although an unfortunate reputation): it is often described as having traditional London working class alongside foreign communities, particularly in South Peckham.

Like so many suburban areas of London, Peckham was a village swallowed up by London and developed as a residential area. Dilapidated old housing in North Peckham was redeveloped in the 1960s and we all know what that means - it became one of the most deprived areas of the UK. But work has been done, including the new Library and the area has seen steady improvement.

Peckham is also one of the centers of the Nigerian-British community, and is sometimes referred to as "Yorubatown" or "Little Lagos".

title: Camberwell
description: Camberwell is a suburban town in the London Borough of Southwark where the Borough Council is based. It is centred around the crossroads at Camberwell Green, a surviving traditional village green. It is made up of Georgian and twentieth century houses. Although it has a train station to the south in Denmark Hill, it does not have a direct link to central London and there have been proposals to build an Underground and Thameslink station here.

title: Bermondsey
description:
POLYGON IUNDER CONSTRUCTION

Bermondsey is an area in London on the south bank of the river Thames, and is part of the London Borough of Southwark. To the west lies Southwark, to the east Rotherhithe, and to the south, Walworth.

title: City of London
description:
This is the actual city of London, often known as "The City" or "The Square Mile". To the west, the part normally assumed to be the centre of London is actually a separate city called Westminster;  both have city status. The City of London is older, being the site of first a Roman town called Londinium, then a walled medieval city. Today, it is a major centre of business and finance.

http://www.cityoflondon.gov.uk/

title: Walworth
description: Walworth is an inner-city area located in the London Borough of Southwark and is a completely residential suburban area. The area has been one of the most deprived parts of London, with the Heygate and Aylesbury Estates showing how not to house people, and is part of the "Walworth Void" which has no tube or train station within it. However, investors are coming back and redevelopment (if you're a councillor) or gentrification (if you're a local) has been taking place in the area.

title: Marylebone
description: Marylebone - pronounced either 'Ma-ri-bun' or 'Mar-lee-bone' - is part of the City of Westminster. Its name comes from a church dedicated to St. Mary be a bourne (stream), and became St. Mary-le-bone, then just Marylebone. The area includes part of London's shopping district as well as a railway station of that name.

title: Regent's Park
description:
A Royal Park planned by John Nash who played an important part in planning London during the 18th Century. Its name comes from Prince George who was officially the Prince Regent. Many villas for his friends were build but many of these do not survive.

Regent's Park is still a major open space in London, and is location of the London Zoo on the northeast corner. There are many gardens, nature areas, lakes and other attractions. It is located mostly in the London Borough of Camden.

This is the park where Pongo from the movie 101 Dalmatians uses the Famous Twilight Bark to warn the London Dogs that his puppies have been stolen by thieves.

title: Southwark / The Borough
description:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IJQNsjtbkIc

Southwark, also known as 'The Borough' started out on the south side of the London Bridge which connnected it to the Roman Capital of Londinium. Southwark has played a role defending the capital from the southern side and was flattened by the Normans in an unsuccessful attempt to attack London.
It is also known as The Borough (invented to distinguish it from The City) and is served by tube stations using both names. Normally, the more historic Borough area is to the southeast around Borough Market and tube station, while Southwark normally refers to "the area on the south side of the Thames". It has a cathedral and has sometimes applied for city status. It became urbanised at an early stage, and now is home to London Bridge railway terminal, the Tate Modern gallery and the reconstructed Globe Theatre. The London Borough of Southwark also covers Peckham, Camberwell and Bermondsey.

title: Bloomsbury
description: Bloomsbury is an area of central London in the south of the London Borough of Camden, developed by the Russell family in the 17th and 18th centuries into a fashionable residential area. It is notable for its array of gardened squares, its literary connections (exemplified by the Bloomsbury Group), and its numerous hospitals and academic institutions.

title: Hyde Park
description:
http://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/hyde_park/

Hyde Park is one of the largest parks in central London, England and one of the Royal Parks of London, famous for its Speakers' Corner.

The park is divided in two by the Serpentine Lake. The park is contiguous with Kensington Gardens, which is widely assumed to be part of Hyde Park, but is technically separate. Hyde Park is 350 acres (1.4 km) and Kensington Gardens is 275 acres (1.1 km) giving an overall area of 625 acres (2.5 km).

The park was the site of The Great Exhibition of 1851, for which the Crystal Palace was designed by Joseph Paxton.

The park has become a traditional location for mass demonstrations. The Chartists, the Suffragettes and the Stop The War Coalition have all held protests in the park.

On 20 July 1982 in the Hyde Park and Regents Park bombings, two bombs linked to the Provisional Irish Republican Army caused the death of eight members of the Household Cavalry and the Royal Green Jackets and seven horses.

title: Westminster
description:
Westminster is an area of London and is the location of the Houses of Parliament - the headquarters of the British Government, along with numerous government offices. The larger City of Westminster is one of the 32 London boroughs and has city status, covering much of central London. Its name means 'West Monastry Church' - which is the Abbey itself, another famous landmark.

Westminster is also quite residential - surprisingly enough, it isn't as expensive as surrounding areas such as Knightsbridge, Pimlico and Chelsea. The name is often used to mean the British government, and Westminster Village refers to the world of British politics.

title: Somers Town
description: Somers Town is a district in central London.

title: Lambeth
description: Lambeth is an area of London on the south side of the river, to the west of Southwark and directly opposite Westminster and Charing Cross. The area is home to the Waterloo Station, the London Eye, Lambeth Palace, the Royal Festival Hall and the Royal National Theatre. The busiest parts of the area are near the river. It gives its name to the London Borough of Lambeth.

title: Nine Elms
description:
An area of London in between Battersea and Vauxhall, is home to the future site of the American Embassy, and the new Covent Garden market. In 1838, it was the first terminus of the London and South Western Railway, however, in 1848 the Terminus moved to Waterloo.

title: Hoxton
description: Hoxton is an area in the London Borough of Hackney, immediately north of the financial district of the City of London.

title: St. George in the East
description: St George in the East was a parish in the metropolitan area of London, England.

title: Kennington
description: Kennington, postal area SE11, is a diverse residential, business, recreational and cultural area with many buildings of architectural and historical interest. Includes the Oval cricket ground, most of Kennington Park and St Mark's Church but does not include (though is adjacent to) Imperial War Museum, Lambeth Palace, Albert Embankment, Vauxhall stations. Boundaries are with SE1, SE17 SW8 and , only just, with SW9 near St Mark's Church.

title: Pimlico
description:
Pimlico is a small area of central London in the City of Westminster that is primarily residential and well known for its collection of small hotels and impressive Regency architecture.

Steve (Stephen) Richard Hackett is a British songwriter and guitarist who was born in Pimlico, London. He played with progressive rock group Genesis, which he joined in 1970. Hackett remained with the band for eight albums before leaving in 1977 to pursue a solo career. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Hackett

title: Mayfair
description: The most expensive neighbourhood to live in in London and home to many embassies, (not classing Kensington Park Gardens as a neighbourhood).  On the British Monopoly Board it is the most expensive property (odd considering the others are all streets). A lot of the area is shops and offices but there are many luxury houses and hotels.

title: Belgravia
description:
Part of the City of Westminster in London. Was owned by Richard Grosvenor in the past, who  started developing it in 1820's. 
 It is relatively quiet district in the heart of London that is characterise by grand terraces and white stucco houses. 
 Belgravia was one of most fashionable districts in London and remains so to this day, estates in Belgravia are one of the most expensive in the world, large house in this area often costs more than $19 million.

title: Stockwell
description: Stockwell is a district in inner south London, England, located in the London Borough of Lambeth.

title: Finsbury
description: Finsbury is a district of central London. It lies immediately north of the City of London and Clerkenwell, west of Shoreditch, and south of Islington and City Road. It is in the south of the London Borough of Islington. The Finsbury Estate is in the western part of the district.

title: Battersea Park
description:
Famous London park opened in 1858 and currently having numerous facilities including comprehensive range of sporting facilities, boating lake, small zoo, exhibition facilities. Refurbished in 2004.

http://www.batterseapark.org/

title: Whitechapel
description: A district of East London in the London Borough of Tower Hamlets which in the 16th century was a suburb used for industries such as tanaries, breweries and slaughterhouses which weren't welcome in the city centre. During the Victorian era it became largely a poor slum where in 1888 Jack the Ripper committed five unsolved murders. It was also here that the Salvation Army was formed and Joseph Merrick, the "Elephant Man", was discovered.

title: Shoreditch
description: Shoreditch is an area of London in the London Borough of Hackney, and is located just outside the city. It has a long history and was one of London's first suburbs but since it has emerged as being affluent and fashionable.

title: St. James's
description: St. James's is part of West-End London and along with much of the West End, it has many low-rise shops and offices but also some expensive residential properties. It is located around St. James's Square.

title: St Luke's
description: An area of the London Borough of Islington, named after a Parish church. Parts of it belong to Finsbury and so sometimes the larger area neames of Islington or Finsbury are used. Also commonly known now as Bunhill or even White Cross after the market.

title: Newington
description: Newington is a district of Central London, England, and part of the London Borough of Southwark.

title: Vauxhall
description: Vauxhall (pronounced 'Vok-zal') is an area of the London Borough of Lambeth home to one of London's busiest bus stations at Vauxhall Cross and a famous MI6 building. The area has new developments on the riverside and the houses of several MPs since it is close to Westminster, as well as some gay venues. It is also the origin of Vauxhall Motors, one of the largest car brands in the UK. It is possible that the Russian word for a railway terminal - 'Vokzal' - originates from here.

title: Clerkenwell
description: Clerkenwell is an area in the northeast of Central London in the London Borough of Islington, and was at one time the Italian area of the city. It has also been famous for radicalism such as Lollards, Chartists and Communists. At one time industrial, the area fell into long decline but in the 1990s slowly improved.

title: Holborn
description: Holborn (traditionally pronounced Hoe-bun, though often now as Hol-bun) is an area of Central London. Originally a hamlet outside the city on the now underground River Fleet, it then became one of London's first suburban areas. Today the area, which is located around the road called Holborn (or High Holborn) is an area of many shopping and entertainment venues.

title: Burgess Park
description: A relatively modern park created from an area of factories and Victorian housing that used to lie on either side of the Grand Surrey Canal. Includes a large pond for fishing and historic sites such as Chumleigh Gardens, the old Wells Way Baths and the neo-classical St George's Church. Although the canal is now filled in it is still possible to walk along its route from its head at the corner of Albany Road and Camberwell Road right into the centre of Peckham.

title: Knightsbridge
description: Knightsbridge is an upmarket major shopping area of London, identified as one of the two international centres (along with the West End) by the Greater London Plan. The area is home to the Knightsbridge Apartments and major stores such Harvey Nichols. It has its own tube station. Most of the developments here happened in the 19th century: before that it was little more than a hamlet on a road notorious for highwaymen.

title: Spitalfields
description: Spitalfields is a former parish in the borough of Tower Hamlets, partly in Central London and partly in the East End of London, near to Liverpool Street station and Brick Lane.

title: Mile End New Town
description: Mile End New Town is a former hamlet within the East End of London. Its area is now part of the London Borough of Tower Hamlets. Following a period of rapid growth it became a hamlet within the large ancient parish of Stepney from 1690, and was split off as a separate ecclesiastical parish in 1841 and civil parish in 1866.

title: Soho
description:
And all of its delights.

Soho is an area in the centre of the West End of London, England, in the City of Westminster. It is an entertainment district which for much of the later part of the 20th century had a reputation for its sex shops as well as its night life and film industry.

title: Aylesbury Estate
description: One of the largest housing estates in London. It dates from the 1960s and was built to house the poorest famillies in London. It has aged very badly: it is one of the most famous examples of Urban Decline in the UK and crime happens as often as every 4 hours. In 2005 it was agreed to have a phased demolition.

title: Duchy of Cornwall Estate - Manor of Kennington - Approximate Area
description:
Many residential properties and some business premises in or near the marked area as well as the Oval Cricket ground used to or still belong to the Duchy of Cornwall. The Duchy's residential properties have a distinctive and attractive style.

http://www.duchyofcornwall.org/aroundtheduchy_london.htm

title: St. James's Park
description:
St. James's Park is a 23 hectare (58 acre) park in Westminster, central London, the oldest of the Royal Parks of London. The park lies at the Southernmost tip of the St. James's area, which was named after a leper hospital dedicated to St. James the Less.

St. James's Park is bounded by Buckingham Palace to the West, The Mall and St. James's Palace to the North, Horse Guards to the East, and Birdcage Walk to the South. The park has a small lake, St. James's Park Lake, with two islands, Duck Island (named for the lake's collection of waterfowl), and West Island. A bridge across the lake affords a Westward view of Buckingham Palace framed by trees and fountains, and a view of the main building of the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, similarly framed, to the East.

The park is the most easterly of a near-continuous chain of parks that also comprise (moving Westward) Green Park, Hyde Park and Kensington Gardens. The closest London Underground stations are St. James's Park, Victoria, and Westminster.

title: Bermondsey Spa
description:
In  the 18th century the discovery of a spring in the area led to Bermondsey becoming a leisure retreat. The spa was established in this area outlined. However, the area fell into a slow decline, and in World war two suffered heavy bombing due to it's proximity to the docklands. Now a group with the partnership of Southwark Council and Hyde Homes has begun the restoration and regeneration of the area, which will, when finished, have over 2000 new homes (40% of which will be affordable), a new Pharmacy, Dental practice, improved community facilities, and new offices and shops. 

http://www.bermondseyspa.co.uk/site/bs_home.php

http://www.bermondseyspa.org.uk/

title: Green Park
description:
Green Park (officially The Green Park) is one of the Royal Parks of London. Covering an area of about 53 acres (21 hectares), it lies between London's Hyde Park and St. James's Park. Together with Kensington Gardens and the gardens of Buckingham Palace, these parks form an almost unbroken stretch of open land reaching from Whitehall and Victoria station to Kensington and Notting Hill.

By contrast with its neighbours, Green Park has no lakes nor any statues or fountains (except for Canada Memorial by Pierre Granche), but consists entirely of wooded meadows. The park is bounded on the south by Constitution Hill, on the east by the pedestrian Queen's Walk, and on the north by Piccadilly. It meets St. James's Park at Queen's Gardens with the Victoria Memorial at its centre, opposite the entrance to Buckingham Palace. To the south is the ceremonial avenue of The Mall, and the buildings of St James's Palace and Clarence House overlook the park to the east. Green Park tube station is located on Piccadilly near the north end of Queen's Walk.

title: Kennington Park
description: Opened in 1854 on site of Kennington Common. Has trees, open areas, sports facilities and dog free play area and adventure playground for children. Also flower and herb garden and rosebeds. As Kennington Common it was the site of public executions, the site of a Chartist rally, and used by orators such as John Wesley (Methodist). Kennington Park was the destination of the first red London bus in 1899.

title: Shaftesbury Park Estate
description: In the Middle Ages this area was known as Pig Hill for its many piggeries, and subsequently became Poupart's Market Garden.  In the 1870s the Artisans, Labourers and General Dwelling Company Housing Co-operative built thousands of small Victorian homes on it for upwardly mobile working people - and deliberately did not include any pubs.  Now a smart residential area.

title: The Garden at Buckingham Palace
description:
Buckingham Palace Garden or, to give it its full title, "The Garden at Buckingham Palace", is generally referred to as the Garden. Situated at the rear of Buckingham Palace, it covers much of the area of the former "Goring Great Garden", named after Lrd Gring, occupant of one of the earliest grand houses on the site. It was laid out by Henry Wise and subsequently redesigned by William Townsend Aiton for George IV.

The Garden occupies a 42 -acre (17 -hectare) site in the City of Westminster, London and has two-and-a-half miles of gravel paths. Its area is bounded by Constitution Hill to the north, Hyde Park Corner to the west, Grosvenor Place to the south-west and the Royal Mews, Queen's Gallery, and Buckingham Palace to the south and east. The planting is varied and exotic, with a mulberry tree dating back to the time of James I of England

Notable features include a large 19th-century lake which is graced by a flock of flamingoes, and the Waterloo Vase. In the Gardens there is a summerhouse, a helicopter pad, and a tennis court.

title: Loughborough Estate
description: Council estate in Lambeth, London.

title: Churchill Gardens Housing Estate
description: Comprising of 1600 homes in 32 blocks, the estate was developed between 1949 and 1962. A notable feature of this estate is that until 1983, it was heated by excess heat from the Battersea Power station.

title: Temple
description:
The Temple is an area of central London, in the vicinity of Temple Church, which is one of the main legal districts of the capital and a notable centre for English law, both historically and in the present day. Two of the four Inns of Court, the Inner Temple and the Middle Temple, are located here and the Royal Courts of Justice are just to the north.

The district contains many barristers' chambers, solicitors' offices, as well as some notable legal institutions such as the Employment Appeal Tribunal. The International Institute for Strategic Studies has its headquarters at Arundel House, near Temple tube station.

The name is recorded in the 12th century as Novum Tumplum, meaning 'New Temple'. It is named from a house belonging to the Knights Templar. The 'Old Temple' was located in Holborn. The name is shared with Inner Temple, Middle Temple, Temple Church and the Temple Bar.

title: Brandon Estate
description: Built in 1958

title: The Serpentine
description: The Serpentine (also known as the Serpentine River) is a 28-acre (11 ha) recreational lake in Hyde Park, London, England, created in 1730. Although it is common to refer to the entire body of water as the Serpentine, strictly the name refers only to the eastern half of the lake. Serpentine Bridge, which marks the boundary between Hyde Park and Kensington Gardens, also marks the western boundary of the Serpentine; the long and narrow western half of the lake is known as the Long Water. The Serpentine takes its name from its snakelike, curving shape.

title: Regents canal
description: Joins the Paddington arm of the Grand Union Canal (opened in 1801) with the River Thames at Limehouse. Work began on 14 October 1812, and the main works were completed four years later in 1820.

title: Barbican Residential Estate
description: The Barbican Estate is a residential estate in the City of London, in an area densely packed with commerce and finance. It also contains, or is adjacent to, the Barbican Arts Centre, the Museum of London, the Guildhall School of Music and Drama, the Barbican public library, the City of London School for Girls and a YMCA, forming the Barbican Complex. With the exception of Milton Court, which contained a fire station, medical facilities and some flats, the complex has been Grade II listed as a whole.

title: Jacob's Island
description:
A rough outline of the area once known as Jacob's Island.
Described by Charles Dickens as "the filthiest, the strangest, the most extraordinary of the many localities that are hidden in London".

title: Hatton Garden
description:
The Hatton Garden area of London (Hatton Garden itself plus adjoining streets) is the traditional centre of the London jewellery trade and houses the capital's major concentration of jewellery workshops, plus many retail jewellery outlets.  On the weekends it is a popular destination for couples seeking to buy engagement rings.  The wholesale gem and jewellery trade is also represented, notably by the world's largest diamond-mining firm, De Beers, which has its global marketing division headquarters in nearby Charterhouse Street.

http://www.hattongardenjewelleryweek.com/history.htm

title: Liberty of Saffron Hill
description:
In 1870-72, John Marius Wilson's Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales described Liberty of Saffron Hill Hatton Garden Ely Rents and Ely Place like this:

SAFFRON-HILL, a liberty and a sub-district in Holborn district, Middlesex; all forming a dense and centralportion of the metropolis. The liberty adjoins the liberties of Hatton-Garden, Ely-Rents, and Ely-Place; and the four liberties comprise 30 acres. Pop. of the four, in 1,851, 8, 728; in 1861, 7, 148. Houses, 643.The sub-district contains also the Charterhouse and St. Sepulchre-without-Newgate, and comprises 60 acres. Pop. in 1851, 13, 837; in 1861, 12,012. Houses, 1, 105.

title: Rockingham Estate
description: Rockingham Estate - Now mostly ex-council however some council owned properties still exist. Rumoured for deomolition 2010+.

title: Covent Garden
description:
Covent Garden (said as Covvent Garden) is an area of the City of Westminster in London. The area is dominated by shopping, street performers and entertainment facilities and contains an entrance to the Royal Opera House Covent Garden, which is also widely known simply as "Covent Garden", and the bustling Seven Dials area. At one time it was the commercial centre of London, although this is now held by Oxford Street.

The Piazza was the site of a flower, fruit and vegetable market from the 1500s until 1974, when the wholesale market relocated to New Covent Garden Market in Nine Elms.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s6c_h_dl6AE

title: Walled Perimeter of  Roman Londinium
description: Roman civitas, founded approximately 43 AD and origin of the modern City of London.  Substantial surviving remains of the fortification Wall are visible outside the Tower of London, and at the Barbican Estate.

title: Dickens Estate
description: The Estate where the late Jade Goody was brought up in.

title: Heygate Estate
description: A residential estate that was completed in 1974. It has ages badly and is due for phased demolition in 2011.

title: Boating Lake
description: http://www.royalparks.gov.uk/parks/regents_park/facilities.cfm

title: Queen Mary's Gardens
description: The most carefully tended section of the park.

title: University College London
description: Main campus

title: Strand
description: Strand was a local government district within the metropolitan area of London, England, from 1855 to 1900.

title: St Thomas' Hospital
description:
St Thomas' Hospital is a large teaching hospital in London, England. It is part of Guy's & St Thomas' NHS Foundation Trust.

+44 20 7188 7188 
http://www.guysandstthomas.nhs.uk/

title: Archbishop's Park
description: This was part of Lambeth Palace grounds. It was separated and became a park in 1901. It still belongs to the Church Commissioners. It has been improved in recent years at the behest and from the work of 'Friends'.

title: London Waterloo station
description: London Waterloo is the largest and busiest of the mainline railway terminals in London. It also has a station on the London Underground. It is the terminus of the lines to the southwest of England, including Southampton, Portsmouth and Bournemouth. The London Underground station serves the Northern, Bakerloo and Jubilee lines along with a short line to Bank. It was opened in 1848 by the London and South Western Railway.
